<br>
I had theorized that perhaps PC damage worked in the same way - but it clearly does not. Hitting against about 5 different mobs, I scored over 40 different hits. So player damage is not so simple as DB + x DI....obviously Strength and Weapon Skill have to have some kind of impact on your damage.<br>
<br>
Now, I had heard that you could find your max damage using the following formula:<br>
<br>
(((STR + Weapon Skill) / 100) * Weapon damage + Damage Bonus<br>
<br>
So for my Throneblade of the Ykesha, that would mean<br>
<br>
(((176 + 185) / 100) * 33 + 11, which comes out to 130.13. My logs only show me as having hit for a maximum in the 120s range, but I haven't logged all that much data so this may well be true. Maybe I should go whack a few decaying skeletons and see if I get my max hit on them...<br>
<br>
In any case, I thought perhaps this formula could be used in some way. When used for a PC, the formula given for a mob's damage only gives the range from the player's minimum hit to their modal hit, around 77 for me. All the hits I'm scoring for 100-120 aren't accounted for.<br>
<br>
Also, I noticed that my hits were not separated in the same way that mob hits are. If a mob has a damage interval of ten, then they're going to hit for 30, 40, 50...etc, while my hits didn't have any constant interval. If your damage interval is truly Weapon damage / 10, then the throneblade has an interval of 3.3, and I was scoring hits for 31 and 32, or 110 and 112, which are too close together to be using that same formula.<br>
<br>
So my theory at this point is that there is another formula which includes something like that ((STR + Weapon skill) / 100 which is used to find your maximum damage, but that that formula is only implemented a certain amount of the time - perhaps it's random? :/<br>
<br>
Something similar to this was posted in the original post, although it put out the idea that perhaps there was a separate percentage for your min hit, your modal hit, your max hit, and the hit which took your strength/skill factor into account. I think it's probably more likely that the min/max hits are just randoms which end up being a 1 or a 20, though, otherwise I may just be saying the same thing in a different way.<br>
<br>
This is speculation, as I'm too tired to sit and try and figure out what the formula is.<br>
<br>
Also, please tell me if you guys already know how to find player damage, because I've posted to a dozen boards on the subject and still have no answers except for things about your ratio, etc. which stopped making sense past level 28. I've been very confused about this topic and I think parsing is boring (that is, trying to find dozens of mobs who are all the same level to kill so that your logs aren't skewed), so I've been trying to find someone who has a formula that makes sense....or just SOME WAY to find out what weapon will have a higher DPS by simply looking at the stats. I have about 8 different weapons on me now, some duel wield, some 2HS, some with procs, some with STR bonuses, and I haven't the foggiest idea any longer how I can tell which one is going to be best. <br>
<br>
Plus, why would I want to parse every single time I got a new weapon? It's far more efficient to just get a formula that I can use before I buy a new weapon.<br>
<br>
Thanks in advance for any light you can shed on this! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vandala2003>Vandala2003</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/9/03 11:37:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1656.topic&index=88>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Mitigation AC</span><hr size=1> You guys have done an unbelievable amount of work on this.  Thank you.  <br>
