 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tugurok>Tugurok</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/bdiebold5/minitug.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 190<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/03 8:53:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1656.topic&index=90>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mitigation AC</span><hr size=1> Sarvis, you misunderstand the model (unless I misunderstand you ;D). Your damage interval is not 33/10, but (maxhit-minhit)/19, as stated in the original model. That adds on to your damage base of (minhit - damage interval), 19 additional times to represent your range of damage values. The frequency distribution within the range should vary based on the relative proportion of your attack to mob ac (presumably), but the values themselves shouldn't.<br>
<br>
By the way, you probably also need to filter your logs for the different types of attacks you have. After all, you probably aren't just swinging the throneblade -- you're also bashing or kicking, which gives you two weapons each with 20 potential damage values (and 40 total, assuming no overlap between them). <p><A href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=140750><img border="0" src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/bdiebold5/tugedit.jpg"></A></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tugurok>Tugurok</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/bdiebold5/minitug.jpg" BORDER=0> at: 1/10/03 8:56:14 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=graalthedorf>Graal the Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 155<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/03 7:42:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1656.topic&index=92>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mitigation AC</span><hr size=1> Sarvis...a couple of things. <br>
<br>
First you may not have ever hit your min hit. You mention this is a short parse...there is nothing to say you ever actually hit for min at all. Min hit = weapon damage/10+DB. That is your min hit. Trust me.<br>
<br>
You mention that you have 18 values between min and mode, but they don't all follow the DI. They won't! You seemed to have missed the part where I mentioned that PC damage is made up of 2 seperate random elements. <br>
<br>
EX. <br>
Swing1 = 4*DI(3.3) + DB(12) =25<br>
Swing2 = 6*DI + DB= 32<br>
Swing3 = 20*DI + DB = 78<br>
<br>
The thing you missed is that those numbers also have a second random amount added to them. Pick any 3 random numbers between 0 and 37*DI(valid at level 60 above a certain atk threshold) and add them respectively to those swings. The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>final result</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> will not be a multiple of DI except by happenstance. <br>
<br>
EX. <br>
Swing1 = 25 + 7 = 32<br>
Swing2 = 32 + 6 = 38<br>
Swing3 = 78 + 5 = 83<br>
<br>
Does that make sense at all?<br>
<br>
<br>
It seems that the most common value for the secondary portion of damage is 0. Take a long parse with a 2 hander and look at the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>peaks</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> between min and mode. <br>
<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14686">Graal MacBladefury</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Crusader of Brell</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=graalthedorf>Graal the Dorf</A> at: 1/10/03 8:54:04 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=graalthedorf>Graal the Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/11/03 6:49:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1656.topic&index=94>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_sword.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Mitigation AC</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Thanks for clearing up that this isn't the case - I'll be sure to only do maximum-minimum/19 from now on.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You can do that for mobs but if you want to do that for PCs you have to use mode instead of max. The DI <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>IS</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> equal to weapon damage/10. It is also equal to (mode-min)/19.<br>
<br>
Assume you have a 50 damage weapon with a damage bonus of 60. Mode hit(20*DI+DB) will be (50/10 * 20)+60...160. Min hit (DI+DB) will be 50/10 +60...65. <br>
<br>
Mode - min /19 = DI<br>
(160-65)/19=5. <br>
weapon damage/10=DI<br>
50/10=5<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Three, I don't totally understand you, Graal. Do you mean that after calculating your damage just like the game would calculate a mob's damage, it suddenly throws in a random number to add to that damage, from 0-37?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yep. If we look at the above weapon numbers (50 damage 60 DB) the weapon would hit for 65, 70, 75, 80....160. Once it has determined that part of damage, it then adds a second random element that ranges from 0 to a constant that is determined by level, STR, and attack. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You said 0-37*DI, but that would be a gigantic number to add on...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
37*DI is right for a level 60 melee that has past a certain atk threshold. What that threshold is I don't know, but I'm guessing it is at least 1200 atk or so, if not more.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>One, how do I calculate maximum hit? I've heard the formula (((STR+Skill)/100)*weapon damage+damage bonus) before, but I don't know if it's correct. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Basically that is correct, at least it is close AFAIK. The problem is that it doesn't take into account +atk items and buffs. Looking at what I have posted above, we know that 20*DI +37*DI is the max that you can hit for at level 60 once you reach a certain threshold of atk. That is 5.7 times weapon damage. That number is a cap on how much +atk items/buffs can raise your max hit, and goes up slightly each level.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It also would imply that there is some way that STR and Skill affects your damage....which it should, but none of the formulas so far have taken either number into account.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The formulas listed have been to show the possible values a mob can hit for. STR and atk do dtermine that max that a PC can hit for, but mainly they determine which of the possible values are hit the most often.<br>
<br>
Let's say you can hit for 5 values...<br>
<br>
low atk you hit for 1, 1, 5, 4, 1, 2, 1, 3, 1, 1, 1, 2, 1, 1, 2, <br>
<br>
high atk you hit for 5, 4, 5, 1, 4, 2, 5, 5, 3, 5, 5, 5, 5, 5, 4, <br>
<br>
That is mainly what STR and atk do. They do increase your max hit up to a certain point, but mainly they just increase the chance you will hit for a higher value. Since most of this discussion has been about NPCs, STR and ATK do not affect the possible values they can hit for at all. They do affect whether the mob will hit mostly for min, or mostly for max, or somewhere in between.<br>
<br>
<br>
